 You'll have the worst headache in your life.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Philetus nodded once more and said nothing.
 He stepped into the corridor with Sustar right behind him.
 The floor was made out of the same plastic as the walls.
 Its surface was rigid, yet unblemished.
 Every step of the way, Philetus felt his feet stick to the floor; it somehow
 made it impossible for someone to slip and fall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
So perfectly designed, so flawless, even after thousands of years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Their steps made no sound; in front of them they could see no more than
 a few feet.
 The panels on the walls lit up as they walked by them and switched off
 when they had passed them by.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Turning sound into trickles of energy.
 Conserving, withholding it.
 They sicken me.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At points, they happened upon crossroads.
 Simple stylized arrows lit up on the floor panels, indicating the proper
 turn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Controlling, directing.
 Herding us like lesser animals.
 I hate them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They were leaving behind them corridors and gangways, doorways and chambers
 that no human had walked ever since the Landing.
 Thousands of years old, yet no-one had trod on them since.
 It wasn't needed; it wasn't allowed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Laws, prohibitions.
 Requests denied, dreams shattered, ground into stardust; helium-3, fuel,
 energy.
 That's all that matters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They reached a recess, an open archway that led into a shaft of sorts.
 It was kept in the dark, but the faint trace of a simple girded ladder
 glinted off the ambient light of the corridor.
 Sustar pointed through the archway with his free hand:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Inside there and up; use the ladder.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Is there no other way?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Just do as I say.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Turning human against human, in the name of mankind.
 How naive, how childish to let the machines decide.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Philetus glanced at Sustar and saw nothing behind his black oblique visor.
 He complied and grabbed the ladder.
 He felt Sustar right behind him, urging him to move.
 He took a few hesitant steps, failing to see where he should put his hands
 and legs.
 Suddenly the darkness dissolved.
 Philetus turned his head to look down and was almost blinded; Sustar had
